{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.43,0.07,0.05,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"516"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45320"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-year history of intermittent rectal bleeding associated with urgency of defaecation. He describes the passage of bright red blood in the pan and on the surface of the faecal material. He has not had any weight loss, night sweats, or fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hypertension, two coronary artery stents inserted after a myocardial infarction three years ago and external beam radiotherapy for carcinoma of the prostate four years ago. His medications include aspirin, clopidogrel and ramipril. He is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the rectum","Radiation proctitis","Aspirin-induced erosions","Anal fissure","Haemorrhoids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation proctitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s long history of rectal bleeding and urgency of defaecation. Proctitis is a well recognised side effect of radiotherapeutic management of prostate cancer and can occasionally produce symptoms of this severity. Radiation associated vascular ectasias can take a long time to develop and bleeding from the lesions may not be immediate evident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignancy\u003C/strong\u003E must always be considered in any case of rectal bleeding, the longevity of the symptoms without weight loss or progression would make such a diagnosis unlikely in this patient. Although this patient may require a colonoscopy to rule out malignancy, it is not the most likely explanation of his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal fissure\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with pain on defaecation and \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin-induced erosions\u003C/strong\u003E causing this clinical picture would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E might produce such a pattern of bleeding, but urgency of defaecation would be unusual and uncharacteristic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radiation proctitis can occur years after radiation therapy for pelvic malignancies.","Rectal bleeding with urgency of defecation is a characteristic presentation of radiation proctitis.","Radiation proctitis should be distinguished from other causes of rectal bleeding such as malignancy, haemorrhoids, and medication-induced mucosal injury."],"references":["Laterza L, Cecinato P, Guido A, Mussetto A, Fuccio L. Management of radiation-induced rectal bleeding. Curr Gastroenterol Rep. 2013;15(11):355\u201362. doi: 10.1007/s11894-013-0355-z. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24145931/","Bhatia M, Suliman H, Ahmed R, Kostadinov D, Singhal T. Radiation Proctitis: A Review of Pathophysiology and Treatment Strategies. Cureus. 2024 Sep 30;16(9):e70581. doi: 10.7759/cureus.70581. PMID: 39483948; PMCID: PMC11525059. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39483948/","McKeown DG, Gasalberti DP, Goldstein S. Radiation Proctitis. 2024 Jan 11. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644721. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32644721/","Tabaja L, Sidani SM. Management of\u00a0Radiation Proctitis. Dig Dis Sci. 2018; 63:2180-2188","Mahmood S, olio S, Steele S, et al. It\u2019s All the RAVE: Time to Give up on the \u201cChronic Radiation Proctitis\u201d Misnomer. Gastroenterology 2021;160:635\u2013638"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T16:00:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-